THE thought that first flashed through the minds of the Hardy boys and Chet was that Ewald had been captured. They thrilled with horror as they debated what might be the fate of the unfortunate man in the hands of the furious and unreasoning crowd.
\par Suddenly they heard a fellow shouting. He was evidently one of the leaders of the surging masses.
\par "Search every main and side road until you find him, boys! We'll hunt him out somehow!" rang out the command.
\par "We must beat that mob to it," snapped the policeman. "We must find Ewald and do it at once."
\par He hustled Luke into his car.
\par "I'll attend to you first and get you to the jail.  You can be glad it isn't you they're after."
\par The colored youth's eyes rolled with terror at the very thought of being hunted by the farmers. Then the officer got in behind the wheel and drove off at great speed.
\par "If we could only find Ruel Rand!" ex\-claimed Frank excitedly.
\par "Let's get moving," Joe suggested. "Maybe we can help the police locate Ewald and get him to safety before the farmers hunt him down."
\par Now that Mrs. Rand had recovered con\-8ciousness, she was in a state of wild anxiety, fearing for the safety of her son.
\par "I want Ewald !" she screamed. "Something has happened to him! I want my boy!"
\par Her heart-rending appeals rang through the house. Miss Fox and the doctor were do\-ing their best to calm her, but with little suc\-cess. She would not be quieted.
\par The boys delayed no longer. They scram-bled into the old automobile and dashed down the driveway toward the Hidden Harbor road.
\par The multitude had scattered, splitting up into groups, which searc
hed each and every section of the place. The Hardys and Chet drove directly to the station house, where only one man was in charge. He was shouting over the telephone when they hurried into the building.
\par "Send us some help !" the fellow was order\-ing. "We can't handle this crowd alone. If they ever catch that guy they'll string him up to the nearest tree. The whole countryside is aroused."
\par He slammed down the receiver, his face drawn with apprehension.
\par "No word of Ewald yet?"
\par "Calls have been coming in from all over town, saying he's been seen in half a dozen places. I've tried to reason with that band and tell 'em it's the crazy Rand they're after, but they won't believe me."
\par "If we only knew where to look for him!" exclaimed Joe.
\par "Anywhere! Everywhere!" cried the officer in distraction. He tossed them a whistle he snatched up from a desk, saying, "If you find him, or if you get into any kind of trouble your\-selves, use that gadget. It may help you."
\par The boys thanked him, and left the station house. The next fifteen minutes they patrolled the roads in the car, every now and then com\-
ing upon some of the searchers. Seeing the boys, the men would yell "Found him yet?" under the impression that the lads were on their side. And the answer would be "Not yet!"
\par Joe,
 Frank and Chet never would forget that night as long as they lived. As the search went on and their quarry eluded capture, the crowd increased in numbers and its temper grew more and more vicious. There would be little or no hope for Ewald now, should he
 fall into their hands.
\par The old car the boys had commandeered from the Rand garage began to grow trouble\-some. The engine spluttered, kicked, and died. The machine lurched to a full stop with unex\-pected suddenness. Frank made several vain attempts to start
 the motor, but nothing seemed to help.
\par "No use!" he said finally. "It's done for." The boys abandoned the car and continued their search on foot. Joe called the attention of his companions to the fact that they seemed to be on a familiar road, for he was 
sure he had seen some of the buildings before.
\par "Seems to me we have been here," he said.
\par "Miss Pennyweather lives in this section."
\par Frank suddenly had an inspiration.
\par "I wonder if Ewald's poor diseased brain would try to devise a method of harming that lady because of her father's plays."
\par "We might go to her home and find out if she is safe," declared Joe.
\par They made their way down the dark highway. When they came in sight of Miss Penny-weather's dwelling the lads saw a light in one of the front windows.
\par Suddenly a dark figure burst forth from the shadow of a clump of trees on the opposite side of the avenue and darted across the road, about twenty yards from the boys.
\par "Perhaps that is Ewald!" gasped Joe.
\par "What can he be up to?" Chet demanded, as the dark figure slunk toward Miss Pennyweather's home. The light fell full upon the face of the man who had sped across the road. It was that of Ewald Rand!
\par There was an expression of maniacal in\-tensity on his face. In each hand he gripped a revolver, and before the boys could move he raised one arm and fired point-blank at the window.
\par "Ewald!" shouted Frank, and all three lads broke into a run.
\par The demented man looked around, and saw the trio sweeping down upon him, but he stood still.
\par There had been a crash of breaking glass as the bullet shattered the window, and Miss Pennyweather who was in the room had leaped to her feet in alarm. To their horror the boys saw the woman slump to the floor in fright.
\par "Ewald! Stop!" cried Frank.
\par But the crazed individual heard nothin
g. He swung around again and fired at the advancing boys, but fortunately the bullet went wide. The Hardys and Chet knew they were risking their lives in attempting to capture the fellow, who was now completely insane with fear, but they felt they could n
ot retreat.
\par "Spread out!" ordered Frank.
\par They scattered, then closed in on their quarry. Ewald Rand, screeching like a tor\-tured owl, fired again aimlessly.
\par Frank ducked and ran toward him, flung him\-self forward, tackled the madman, and brought him down. As he did so, the guns flew out of Ewald's hands.
\par Then there ensued a terrific struggle. The boys were surprised at the fellow's strength. They rolled over and over in the roadway, clinging desperately to their prisoner.
